1
00:00:00,940 --> 00:00:05,680
Many traders use moving averages to follow
the trend and to identify changes in market

2
00:00:05,680 --> 00:00:06,680
direction.

3
00:00:06,680 --> 00:00:10,299
While moving averages are a useful tool to
have in your toolbox, they can provide false

4
00:00:10,299 --> 00:00:12,090
signals quite a lot.

5
00:00:12,090 --> 00:00:17,360
One method to filter market noise and remove
a part of those false signals is to use moving

6
00:00:17,360 --> 00:00:18,360
average envelopes.

7
00:00:18,360 --> 00:00:22,260
In today’s video, you’ll discover how
to trade using envelopes and I’ll share

8
00:00:22,260 --> 00:00:26,250
several strategies using this indicator.

9
00:00:26,250 --> 00:00:31,570
The Envelopes is a tool that attempts to identify
the upper and lower bands of a trading range.

10
00:00:31,570 --> 00:00:36,199
It does this by plotting two moving average
envelopes on a price chart, one shifted up

11
00:00:36,199 --> 00:00:39,420
to a certain distance above, and one shifted
below.

12
00:00:39,420 --> 00:00:43,710
The idea behind this indicator is that the
price has the tendency to remain within a

13
00:00:43,710 --> 00:00:46,519
certain range during normal market conditions.

14
00:00:46,519 --> 00:00:51,149
However, when these conditions are changing
the price has the potential to move above

15
00:00:51,149 --> 00:00:56,999
or below the envelope bands, which is signaling
possible trading positions.

16
00:00:56,999 --> 00:01:02,489
Moving Average Envelopes consist of a moving
average plus and minus a percentage deviation.

17
00:01:02,489 --> 00:01:06,720
When you apply the envelope indicator, you
will notice two lines or bands which appear

18
00:01:06,720 --> 00:01:10,980
above and below the price and these lines
are called upper and lower envelopes.

19
00:01:10,980 --> 00:01:14,720
Also, the area between the bands represents
the channel.

20
00:01:14,720 --> 00:01:16,930
The line within the channel is moving average.

21
00:01:16,930 --> 00:01:21,460
You can see that the bands move in parallel
with the moving average because the distance

22
00:01:21,460 --> 00:01:23,830
away from the moving average is constant.

23
00:01:23,830 --> 00:01:27,890
Each envelope is set the same percentage above
or below the moving average.

24
00:01:27,890 --> 00:01:31,740
This creates the parallel bands that follow
price action.

25
00:01:31,740 --> 00:01:37,320
Now, the selection of period of the moving
average and the percentage of envelopes is

26
00:01:37,320 --> 00:01:40,070
what makes or breaks your trading strategy.

27
00:01:40,070 --> 00:01:45,060
The parameters for the Moving Average Envelopes
depend on your trading or investing objectives

28
00:01:45,060 --> 00:01:48,310
and the characteristics of the market you
are trading.

29
00:01:48,310 --> 00:01:54,060
Day traders and scalpers will likely use shorter
(faster) moving averages and relatively tight

30
00:01:54,060 --> 00:01:55,060
envelopes.

31
00:01:55,060 --> 00:02:00,110
Swing traders and investors will likely prefer
longer (slower) moving averages with wider

32
00:02:00,110 --> 00:02:01,110
envelopes.

33
00:02:01,110 --> 00:02:06,060
The market volatility will also influence
the parameters.

34
00:02:06,060 --> 00:02:10,200
When you plot the envelopes on your chart,
you probably see the resemblance with Bollinger

35
00:02:10,200 --> 00:02:11,890
Bands and Keltner Channel.

36
00:02:11,890 --> 00:02:16,260
Well, these indicators will adjust by themselves
to market volatility.

37
00:02:16,260 --> 00:02:20,250
Bollinger Bands use the standard deviation
to set bandwidth.

38
00:02:20,250 --> 00:02:24,150
Keltner Channels use the Average True Range
(ATR) to set channel width.

39
00:02:24,150 --> 00:02:28,810
Well, with envelopes, you must independently
account for volatility when setting the Moving

40
00:02:28,810 --> 00:02:30,200
Average Envelopes.

41
00:02:30,200 --> 00:02:36,980
Stocks with high volatility will require wider
bands to encompass most price action, while

42
00:02:36,980 --> 00:02:41,610
markets with low volatility can use narrower
bands.

43
00:02:41,610 --> 00:02:45,980
In choosing the right parameters, it often
helps to overlay a few different Moving Average

44
00:02:45,980 --> 00:02:47,570
Envelopes and compare.

45
00:02:47,570 --> 00:02:53,580
For example, this chart contains 2 Moving
Average Envelopes based on the 21-day SMA.

46
00:02:53,580 --> 00:03:00,370
The 3% envelopes were touched several times,
while the 5% envelopes were only touched rarely.

47
00:03:00,370 --> 00:03:20,100
A swing trader might use the 5% envelopes,
while a short-term trader could use the 3%

48
00:03:20,100 --> 00:03:34,830
envelopes.

49
00:03:34,830 --> 00:03:36,370
So how to read the envelopes?

50
00:03:36,370 --> 00:03:41,780
With a moving average as the base, Moving
Average Envelopes can be used as a trend following

51
00:03:41,780 --> 00:03:42,780
indicator.

52
00:03:42,780 --> 00:03:47,650
Beyond simply trend following, the envelopes
can also be used to identify overbought and

53
00:03:47,650 --> 00:03:52,420
oversold levels when the trend is relatively
flat and also to provide dynamic support and

54
00:03:52,420 --> 00:03:53,790
resistance.

55
00:03:53,790 --> 00:03:58,370
The moving average envelopes smooths out price
fluctuations and allows us to see the bigger

56
00:03:58,370 --> 00:04:00,270
picture of the market.

57
00:04:00,270 --> 00:04:05,080
With the Envelopes, you can look at the direction
of the bands to get an idea about the trend.

58
00:04:05,080 --> 00:04:09,379
If the bands are sloping upward, then it confirms
an uptrend.

59
00:04:09,379 --> 00:04:12,930
If the bands are sloping downward, it confirms
a downtrend.

60
00:04:12,930 --> 00:04:19,049
When the envelopes are moving sideways, price
is neither in an uptrend or downtrend.

61
00:04:19,049 --> 00:04:22,820
Although different traders have their own
way in which they use the envelope and try

62
00:04:22,820 --> 00:04:27,260
to identify specific patterns, the common
application of the indicator is to provide

63
00:04:27,260 --> 00:04:33,940
certain alerts such as overbought or oversold,
sell and buy signals or as a trend confirmation.

64
00:04:33,940 --> 00:04:38,460
If you use narrow envelopes, when prices are
done resting and consolidating, they will

65
00:04:38,460 --> 00:04:42,720
break out of envelopes, in one direction or
the other.

66
00:04:42,720 --> 00:04:47,420
A trader might view prices breaking above
the upper envelope as a potential buy opportunity.

67
00:04:47,420 --> 00:04:53,730
And when prices break below the lower envelope,
a trader might view that as a selling opportunity.

68
00:04:53,730 --> 00:04:59,190
Basically, Moving Average Envelopes can be
used to identify strong moves that signal

69
00:04:59,190 --> 00:05:01,970
the start of an extended trend.

70
00:05:01,970 --> 00:05:06,620
The trick, as always, is picking the correct
parameters, which takes practice, trial and

71
00:05:06,620 --> 00:05:07,620
error.

72
00:05:07,620 --> 00:05:12,060
In this example notice how the price broke
above the upper envelope and continued moving

73
00:05:12,060 --> 00:05:13,560
above this band.

74
00:05:13,560 --> 00:05:15,520
This shows buying strength.

75
00:05:15,520 --> 00:05:18,470
The inverse logic can be applied for a downtrend.

76
00:05:18,470 --> 00:05:25,070
A strong move below the lower envelope signals
weakness that can foreshadow an extended downtrend.

77
00:05:25,070 --> 00:05:30,500
Remember, if you want to chase breakout moves,
use narrow envelopes.

78
00:05:30,500 --> 00:05:35,800
Now, the majority of price breakouts do not
go on to form new trends.

79
00:05:35,800 --> 00:05:40,620
They will instead more frequently revert back
into the previous price range.

80
00:05:40,620 --> 00:05:44,780
If you are familiar with Bollinger Bands,
you probably now that a common strategy is

81
00:05:44,780 --> 00:05:49,070
to sell near the upper band and to buy near
the lower band.

82
00:05:49,070 --> 00:05:51,419
This could also be applied to envelopes.

83
00:05:51,419 --> 00:05:56,530
Moving Average Envelopes make great overbought
and oversold indicators, when using higher

84
00:05:56,530 --> 00:05:58,070
parameters.

85
00:05:58,070 --> 00:06:02,960
Using the concept of range trading, you could
buy when the price penetrates the lower envelope

86
00:06:02,960 --> 00:06:05,460
and closes back inside the envelope.

87
00:06:05,460 --> 00:06:10,950
Likewise, you might sell when the price penetrates
the upper envelope and then closes back down

88
00:06:10,950 --> 00:06:13,770
inside the envelope.

89
00:06:13,770 --> 00:06:18,960
In this example, notice there are times when
price initially moves above or below an envelope

90
00:06:18,960 --> 00:06:20,600
but turns back around.

91
00:06:20,600 --> 00:06:24,290
This usually happens when the moving average
slope is FLAT.

92
00:06:24,290 --> 00:06:28,680
When this happens, moving average envelopes
can be used to identify overbought and oversold

93
00:06:28,680 --> 00:06:30,100
levels.

94
00:06:30,100 --> 00:06:34,050
When price moves above the upper envelope,
this can be considered overbought.

95
00:06:34,050 --> 00:06:39,100
When price moves below the lower envelope,
this can be considered oversold.

96
00:06:39,100 --> 00:06:43,270
However, identifying overbought and oversold
levels isn’t easy.

97
00:06:43,270 --> 00:06:47,710
Remember, price can become overbought and
remain overbought when the bullish trend is

98
00:06:47,710 --> 00:06:48,710
strong.

99
00:06:48,710 --> 00:06:50,639
The same goes for being oversold.

100
00:06:50,639 --> 00:06:55,400
This is why it’s best to pay attention to
the slope of the moving average and make sure

101
00:06:55,400 --> 00:06:57,350
it’s flat.

102
00:06:57,350 --> 00:07:03,960
Here, notice how the 20 MA and the upper and
lower envelopes are flat…almost horizontal

103
00:07:03,960 --> 00:07:04,960
even.

104
00:07:04,960 --> 00:07:07,350
Basically, the price is directionless here.

105
00:07:07,350 --> 00:07:11,420
There is no strong bullish trend, nor is there
a strong bearish trend.

106
00:07:11,420 --> 00:07:15,520
Observe how the upper envelope acts as a strong
resistance level.

107
00:07:15,520 --> 00:07:20,169
Whenever price traded near the upper envelope,
price would fall back down.

108
00:07:20,169 --> 00:07:21,860
The same with the lower envelope.

109
00:07:21,860 --> 00:07:24,759
Observe how it acts as a strong support level.

110
00:07:24,759 --> 00:07:30,860
Whenever price traded near the lower envelope,
price would bounce back up.

111
00:07:30,860 --> 00:07:34,020
Envelopes are also great for buying or selling
pullbacks.

112
00:07:34,020 --> 00:07:38,900
If the last high was let’s say five percent
above the moving average, keep the upper envelope

113
00:07:38,900 --> 00:07:44,270
line set at five percent—the next high will
often reflect the same extreme.

114
00:07:44,270 --> 00:07:49,449
Conversely, if the last significant downswing
low was five percent below the moving average,

115
00:07:49,449 --> 00:07:54,930
keep this figure as the lower envelope setting
until market action dictates otherwise.

116
00:07:54,930 --> 00:07:58,800
In this example, notice this great entry at
the lower envelope.

117
00:07:58,800 --> 00:08:04,460
The market made a swing low here, and respected
the dynamic support offered by the lower envelopes

118
00:08:04,460 --> 00:08:07,550
the second time the price reached the area.

119
00:08:07,550 --> 00:08:12,380
The envelopes also serve as dynamic support
and resistance areas.

120
00:08:12,380 --> 00:08:17,110
If prices cross above the moving average,
assume that this line will act as support

121
00:08:17,110 --> 00:08:22,070
on pullbacks and the next rally will have
the potential to advance to the upper envelope

122
00:08:22,070 --> 00:08:23,070
line.

123
00:08:23,070 --> 00:08:29,640
If the price is in an uptrend, the upper envelope
line may act as a rising dynamic line of resistance.

124
00:08:29,640 --> 00:08:34,520
The rally tops will hug the upper envelope
line, but prices will tend to keep going up.

125
00:08:34,520 --> 00:08:39,870
So, in an uptrend, the upper envelope is a
great take profit zone.

126
00:08:39,870 --> 00:08:45,040
If prices cross below the center moving average,
assume that this line will act as resistance

127
00:08:45,040 --> 00:08:49,380
on any rebounds and that downside potential
is to the lower envelope line.

128
00:08:49,380 --> 00:08:54,360
If the trend is down, the lower envelope line
may act as a falling dynamic support line.

129
00:08:54,360 --> 00:08:58,680
The lower envelope is a potential take profit
zone.

130
00:08:58,680 --> 00:09:02,680
In an uptrend, price could decline to the
lower envelope line.

131
00:09:02,680 --> 00:09:07,529
This area will define where the price is both
oversold and the specific price area that

132
00:09:07,529 --> 00:09:09,550
offers a potential buying opportunity.

133
00:09:09,550 --> 00:09:14,149
In a downtrend, price could advance to the
upper envelope line.

134
00:09:14,149 --> 00:09:18,790
This area will help define where the market
is both overbought and the specific price

135
00:09:18,790 --> 00:09:23,630
area that may be most opportune as a selling
point.

136
00:09:23,630 --> 00:09:26,730
Remember that moving averages are lagging
indicators.

137
00:09:26,730 --> 00:09:31,760
This is because the price data always incorporates
periods of the past, so the inflexions in

138
00:09:31,760 --> 00:09:37,120
the market's direction will always be reflected
more slowly by a moving average, rather than

139
00:09:37,120 --> 00:09:38,350
by the price itself.

140
00:09:38,350 --> 00:09:43,459
How much more slowly, is a function of the
size of the period you choose.

141
00:09:43,459 --> 00:09:48,931
In some cases, you may find that using a combination
of more than one set of envelopes (say, one

142
00:09:48,931 --> 00:09:54,070
with a longer period and one with a shorter
period) may paint a fuller picture.

143
00:09:54,070 --> 00:09:58,750
Really the best way to establish what works
with your own trading style is to go ahead

144
00:09:58,750 --> 00:10:01,990
and back test different periods in different
time frames.

145
00:10:01,990 --> 00:10:07,660
Also, it goes without saying, building a complete
Envelope strategy is not just about signals

146
00:10:07,660 --> 00:10:10,160
informing you when to buy and sell.

147
00:10:10,160 --> 00:10:12,470
Envelopes are just a part of the full story.

148
00:10:12,470 --> 00:10:17,350
Price action, support and resistance and a
solid risk management are also needed to get

149
00:10:17,350 --> 00:10:19,720
the best out of envelopes.

150
00:10:19,720 --> 00:10:24,890
As always, if you learned something new and
found value, leave us a like to show your

151
00:10:24,890 --> 00:10:28,610
support, subscribe to our channel and click
the bell icon to stay in touch when we upload

152
00:10:28,610 --> 00:10:29,940
new videos.

153
00:10:29,940 --> 00:10:30,940
Until next time.

